     {q:"A volcano is an opening in the Earth’s surface through which melted rock, called ___, can escape.", options:["Sand, which is not connected to volcanic eruptions","Lava","A concept unrelated to how volcanoes work","Ice, which is not connected to volcanic eruptions"], answer:1},
     {q:"Which is an example of what might happen during an earthquake?", options:["A concept unrelated to earthquakes","The ground shakes suddenly","The weather instantly becomes sunny","Nothing at all happens to the ground"], answer:1},
     {q:"Why do scientists study volcanoes and earthquakes, even though these events can be dangerous?", options:["This concept has no relevance to understanding the Earth","Understanding these events can help predict them and keep people safer when they occur","These events never actually pose any danger to people","Studying volcanoes and earthquakes provides no useful information at all"], answer:1},
     {q:"Why might scientists say that volcanoes and earthquakes show that the Earth’s surface is always changing?", options:["The Earth’s surface never changes in any way","Volcanoes and earthquakes have no connection to the Earth’s surface","These events reveal that forces beneath the surface can reshape the land, even though the changes are not always visible","This concept has no relevance to understanding Earth science"], answer:2}
